1 (ix) Forestry practices; and
2 (x) Resource options that promote the multiple benefits of forest
3 management;
4 (2) Providing outreach and engagement that builds local capacity and
5 institutionalizes sustainability efforts within communities and the district forestry boards,
6 including:
7 (i) Holding a forest sustainability conference once every 2 years;
8 (ii) Implementing a peer–to–peer learning exchange; and
9 (iii) Providing healthy forest presentations;
10 (3) Developing and expanding a healthy forest education and conservation
11 program;
12 (4) Improving the outreach of district forestry boards by providing
13 education, recognition, strategies, and actions the boards can implement;
14 (5) Providing small grants to district forestry boards, forest landowners,
15 local governments, and businesses to test innovative best management practices in
16 forestry;
17 (6) Recognizing the efforts forest landowners and local governments make
18 toward achieving healthy, sustainable forest management; and
19 (7) Expenses related to the administration of the Fund.
20 (h) (1) The State Treasurer shall invest the money of the Fund in the same
21 manner as other State money may be invested.
22 (2) Any interest earnings of the Fund shall be credited to the Fund.
23 (i) Expenditures from the Fund may be made only in accordance with the State
24 budget.
25 (j) Money expended from the Fund for the outreach, training, education, and
26 grants under subsection (g) of this section is supplemental to and is not intended to take
27 the place of funding that otherwise would be appropriated for forestry education and
28 outreach.
29 (k) For fiscal years 2025 [and 2026] THROUGH 2031, the Governor shall include
30 in the annual budget bill an appropriation of $250,000 to the Fund.

